## Why This Exercise Matters Beyond Documentation

I want to be honest that my initial reaction to Task P-8 was mild skepticism. After the substantive work of the past ten days — risk registers, monitoring strategies, control tailoring — writing a mission statement felt like a documentation formality. But working through it carefully changed my view.

The mission and business purpose documentation does three things that are genuinely useful:

**First, it grounds technical security decisions in human outcomes.** When the question is "should we require MFA for all OpenMRS user accounts?" the answer is obviously yes from a security standpoint. But the mission documentation makes the *why* explicit — because the system holds the health information of patients who have trusted us with it, and unauthorized access to that information causes real harm to real people. That framing matters when communicating security requirements to stakeholders who may push back on controls that add friction to clinical workflows.

**Second, it establishes the justification for the High impact categorization.** A reviewer looking at the System Security Plan for OpenMRS needs to understand why the system is categorized as High before the categorization is credible. The mission documentation provides that context — it explains who depends on the system, for what, and what the consequences of failure are. The High categorization flows naturally from that explanation rather than appearing as an arbitrary choice.

**Third, it sets the frame for the entire security program.** Every control, every policy, every monitoring activity in this project exists to protect the mission described in Task P-8. When the program feels overwhelming — when the number of controls is large and the resources are limited — the mission statement is the prioritization filter. Which controls most directly protect the ability to deliver safe care? Those come first.

