## Connecting the Mission to Previous Work

Looking back at the work done in Days 21 through 30, the mission documentation connects to almost everything:

The **risk appetite statement** from Day 23 — very low tolerance for ePHI exposure, low tolerance for extended unavailability — flows directly from the mission. Those tolerances are set that way because the mission depends on data confidentiality and system availability.

The **enterprise risk register** from Day 24 — ransomware, insider access, third-party failure — represents threats to the mission. Each risk is ultimately a risk to the organization's ability to deliver safe, continuous, coordinated care.

The **FIPS 199 High categorization** from Day 29 is justified by the mission. High confidentiality because patients have trusted us with sensitive information. High integrity because care decisions depend on accurate records. High availability because clinical operations depend on system uptime.

The **continuous monitoring strategy** from Day 30 exists to protect the mission. The monitoring activities are not ends in themselves — they are how the organization maintains confidence that OpenMRS continues to serve its mission safely.

The mission is not a separate document. It is the foundation that the rest of the security program sits on.

