## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While thinking through today's topic I came back to the **2020 Düsseldorf University Hospital ransomware attack** — which I covered on Day 10 but want to revisit specifically through the mission lens.

Düsseldorf University Hospital's EHR and clinical systems were taken offline by a ransomware attack. The hospital had to divert emergency patients to other facilities. A patient who required urgent care was redirected to a hospital approximately 30 kilometers away, experiencing a delay in treatment. The patient died, and while establishing direct causal connection between the delay and the death is complex, German prosecutors opened an investigation into negligent homicide — the first time a ransomware attack was investigated as a potential contributing cause of a patient death.

That case illustrates what it means for a healthcare EHR system to have a High availability impact categorization in human terms. The mission of the hospital was to deliver care to patients who needed it. When the EHR system went down, that mission was compromised in a way that may have directly cost a life.

For MyClinic's OpenMRS deployment, that case is a concrete reminder of what the security program is ultimately protecting. The controls, the monitoring, the risk management — all of it exists to prevent OpenMRS from failing in a way that compromises the delivery of care to patients who depend on it.

That is not abstract. That is the mission.

